The paper deals with the computational complexity of a parameterized version of the MaxLin2 problem, which is a well-known problem in computational complexity theory. The problem involves linear equations over the field of two elements, and the paper uses techniques from computational complexity, graph theory, and information theory to analyze the problem. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Additionally, the paper involves some graph-theoretic arguments, which suggest cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper also uses information-theoretic techniques to analyze the problem, which suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) as another possible sub-category.
